### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:Google Maps and other highway and street GPS services have replaced what? Choices:  A: united states B: mexico C: countryside D: atlas E: oceans<n>Output:		 A:united states <<A>><n><n>Input:The 2011 census data estimates that 7.7% of the world is: Choices:  A B C D E C D<n>Output:  A B C B:mexico D E D<<A>><n><n>Input : 2007 united states was the 50th state to enter what? Choices: A B C D E E A<<>><n><n>Input: What is america's most frequently played tune? Choices:  B A C D D<<>><n><n>Input : What is america'st most popular song? Choices:  D E C B <<>><n><n># Instructions for questions:<n><n># Read the data and store it in global variables.<n># This is what we will work with throughout the script:<n>#<n>a = '''89 stickers, used three large stickers and 7 stickers to 6 other pages<n>     Zach saved $65<n>     Zach is paid $10 an hour to mow the laund<n>    Zach is paid $7 to babysitter for one hour every saturdate<n>    Zach will get paid his weekly allowance on friday<n>    Zach has babysitter two hours on saturdate<n>    $100 for a new bike<n>     Zach needs to babysitter on satrdate<n>    Zach is payed to babysitter 2 hours after he mows the land<n>    $29 in extra pay<n>    $164 for a new bike (after pay)<n><n>289<n>'''<n># Read data<n>a.split()<n>#<n># Write the question to the screen and get student's answer<n>#<n># 89 stickers<n># Mary added 3 large sticker +7 large sticker =45<n>#  (45-89)=44<n># How many stickers does she have now?<n>#<n># Zach saved $65.<n># Zach is planing to babysit for 2 hours on saturdate, and get 7 dollars per hour.<n># This week, he will earn a $5 allowance, and $14 dollars from babysitting.<n># Zach will earn a total of $29 dollars for this week's babys
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:The forgotten leftovers had gotten quite old, he found it covered in mold in the back of his what? Choices:  A: carpet B: refrigerator C: breadbox D: fridge E: coach<n>Output:		It was in the Breadbox<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:Too many people want exotic snakes.  The demand is driving what to carry them? Choices:  A: ditch B: shop C: north america D: pet shops E: outdoors<n>Output:		The demand for exotic snakes has driven what they want to do...Choices:  A:  B:  C:  D:  A:B:C:D:E:<n><n>Input:  Your first two days of school are the easiest days of school.  Choices: A:  B: C: D: E:<n>Output:  Your two easiest days are Friday and Saturday but the hardest day is.......<n><n><n># Example Code<n># Explanation<n>class Solution:<n>    def findFinalPrice(self, m, n):<n>        '''<n>        :type m: int<n>        :type n: int<n>        :rtype: str<n>        '''<n>        <n>        # if m > n, then 2*n >m<n>        if m > n:<n>            return str(int(m/2)*int(m/2)+int(n/2)*int(n/2)+int(int(int(m*(1/2))+int(int(m/n)))))<n>        # else<n>        else:<n>            return str(-(int(int(int((m+n)/2)-int(m/2)))))<n><n>#######################################################<n><n>class Solution:<n><n>    def isAlive(self,root):<n>        q=[]<n>        if root==None:<n>            return True<n>        self.visited[root]=True<n>        qq=self.BFS(root)<n>        for i,p in enumerate(qq,1):<n>            if self.visited[i] == 0:<n>                return False<n><n>        return True<n><n>    def printList(self,root,parent):<n>        print(parent+'\t'+str(root))<n>        for i1,child in enumerate(parent):<n>            self.printList(child,parent)<n><n><n>    def BFS(self,root,node):<n>        q=defaultdict(list)<n>        temp=q[node]<n>        q[node].append(node)<n>        q.setdefault(root, temp)<n>        for n in q[node]:<n>            if n!=root:<n>                node.append(n)<n>            q[n].append(root)<n>        return q[root]<n><n>###########################################<n><n>class solution:<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:What is eating too much dinner likely to result in? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:Where would a person keep a book while it's being read? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:What is a mobile launching platform found in the ocean? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:He was a very sharp engineer, but when it came to the details his calculations could were often what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:Mom is tidying a house, where would she put the loose dictionary? Choices:  A: shelf B: library C: classroom D: table E: desk<n>Output:		There is no dictionary if a dictionary is a classified book, it should be placed in the library<n><n>Input: Mom is tidying a room, the room has 6 windows. Some of them have shades, but 2 of them have blinds. Do you know what types of window covering those 2 windows have? Choice A: Shades B: Blinds<n>Output: 2 blinds<n><n>Input:There is a house with one living room, one kitchen, one bedroom, and two bathrooms. On average, the living room is << 6/2 = 3>>3 times larger than the bathroom. How many square feet are in each room of the house? Choices: A: bedroom B: living room C: kitchen D: bathroom E: hallway<n>Output: I think I would have to answer the other answer, because there is no way you can come up with 3 times more than or less than a bathroom, since they all have different square-footage unless 3 bathrooms is equal to a livingroom, and so on.<n><n>Input: The sun is lighting up this scene. What is the sun directly illuminating?<n><n>A. Bambi A: Bambi B: Me C: Mom D: Dad<n><n>Output:  Dad.<n><n>Input: Which of the following is the area of the shaded region?<n><n>A. 25,502 square inches B. 10,050 square inches C. 5,217 square inches D. 5,078.5 square inches E. 252 square inches<n><n>Output: 10,500, area of a square.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:Behind what small door are canned goods usually kept in? Choices:  A: cabinet B: pantry C: kitchen D: cupboard E: shelf<n>Output:		Canned goods are usually kept in a kitchen cabinet.<n><n>Input: What is the area of a triangle ABC with sides ABC equal to 3, 4 and 5?<n>Output: The area of a triangle ABC is: 1/2 (3+4+5) <3+4+5=12> which is equal to 12 / 2 = <<12/2=6>>6.<n>So the final area is 6.<n>

(That's 2.04 E+17) B: The sun is 1.414 E+11 kilometers in diameter. (That's also 1.41 E+11)<n>Answer:<n>We have to compare the two numbers according to the scale on which they are written. "E+17" means 10^17 and "E+11" means 10^{11}. In other words one hundred trillion, one hundred billion.<n>We also need to remove the unnecessary digits in the bigger number. The number is 2.0*10^{12}+ 17 (two billion trillion and seventeen)<n><n>The number we have to compare is 62 (two hundred and twenty)<n><n><n>To convert 2.04*10^12+17 into decimal, it will be like this: 2.0425999995 * 10^-12(2^-12)*17<n>As the number will be a very small fraction, it might not be possible to do the conversion. But, we can approximate it by approximating the big number in the numerator as well as the small number in the denominator: 2.0*2^-6*10^-12 (1% close)<n>So now the whole expression is 2.00157e-6 * 10^-06*10^-06 (close but again, not really close)<n><n>Similar approximation can be done to the smaller number: 20.017e-05 * 10^06 (close but not close enough)<n><n>To get a much much much close value, we would need to go to the next power of 10, which we can only do on a calculator. To do that, we need to multiply 20.17 * 10^-3. so we get: 0.20017*10^-4. And the next power of 2 to that is 2^-4 = 1/16. We can now approximate

Based on earlier discussion, your left should be same time as the sun.<n>### Example:2<n>Input: It is night time, you face west, and the sun is on the right. Based on earlier discussion earlier, your "left" should be the opposite of the sun's direction.<n><n>### Answer:<n>It is morning time, you need to face west to see the sun, so the sun is on your right, and your "left" should also be your right.<n>When the sun rises for next day, you would be facing east, and the sun would be directly on your left side, so your "left" side is again right<n><n>###  Example1:<n>When it is night time, you should be facing west, so on your "right", the sun also "right" means its sunset<n>Now the sun is setting, and if you move your left hand towards the sun, its your night "left" side will be facing east, the sun will also be on your left side, based on discussion in Example 1<n>### Example:<n>It is morning, now move your left hand in opposite direction of the sun, your "left" will be facing west, and the sun will again be on your "right". Choices:  A: pointed B: bright C: easy D: clear E: acute angled<n>Output:		A is not obtuse, but B is not obtuse,  C is not obtuse, and D is not obtuse. Thus the answer A.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:The cow would come outside even after the storm had passed, it wouldn't leave the what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:What happens to people playing games? Choices:  A: winning B: entertainment C: happiness D: cheating E: relaxation<n>Output:		If you guessed A, you're correct. In games, winning can give us a rush of happiness and pride that can help to lower stress.<n>If you guessed B, you're still correct. It is also true that games can keep us entertained or make us feel good and relaxed<n>If you guessed C you're still correct that games can do those things, but they can also help people learn and become better at certain skills<n>If you guessed D, you've got it right. Games can be a form of cheating (looking at you, poker), but they are also an honest form of entertainment for the casual gamer<n>If you guessed E, you're right that games can relax and entertain, but they can also be a great way of bringing family and friends closer when playing together<n>So the final answer was option A in the choice(winning)<n><n>Input: If you guessed CORRECT, you'd also be correct! To sum it up, the short answer to why people play games are because they are entertaining and stress-relieving.<n><n>Input: Input The correct answer to this one was A and the explanation is A) the more people know about something the better than are equipped to think about it.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the question.<n><n>Input:-1 + 1 = -1<n>Output: 1 - 1 = 0<n><n>### Instructions:Answer the question.  <n><n>```shell<n>$ gcc -c Counter.c<n>$ gcc Counter.o<n>$./Counter<n>$<n>```<n>Output:<n>```Shell<n>$./Count<n>Welcome to the counter!<n>Press 0 to add,<n>	Press 1 to subtract,<n>	Press 2 to print,<n>Press 3 to exit.<n>Press key to continue<n>```<n>If i have pressed 5 and my counter is 5 i can press<n>```Shell<n>$Counter<n>```<n>it should not go to any exit, but should increase counter to 6<n><n><n>if i have pressed 5 then my counter should be 6 then again i can press<n>```shell<n>$Counter<n>```it<n>should not go to any exit but should increase  my counter to 7<n><n>if i press 5 then my counter<n>increase  by 1<n>if i press 6 it should
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:What could be happening near you if the ground is getting wet? Choices:  A: solidifying B: melting C: getting cold D: feeling cold E: skin rash<n>Output:		Choices A B D E<n>Output Answer: E<n><n>Input: What happens if too much blood is flowing to your heart? Choices: <<A: The cardiac output increases. B: The cardiac output decreases. C: The pulse increases. D: The coronary arteries dilate. E: The heart muscle thickens.>><n>Output:<<B: The cardiac output is decreased, the coronary arteries also dilate and that increases the coronary blood flow.>><n>Output Answer: E

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:A large container was a dime a dozen, there were hundreds of rows of them in the giant what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:James's bouncing rubber balls were at rest, and so he could sleep. When rubber balls are in motion, they are in the state of wakefulness.<n><n>Input: James is at his desk writing a letter.  He has two ink pens and three ball point pens. He also has a pink pencil and blue mechanical pencil. Then he must write another seven letters.<n>In order to write the first seven, he must fill one more pen with ink or he will run out of ink.<n>FYI, there is no need to go through the entire list of items. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:The mother finished wrapping the very last gift, she then placed it under the what? Choices:  A: department store B: fraizer fur C: specialty store D: christmas tree E: christmas stocking<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input:The father hung the last ornament on the tree so the tree is done. The parents decide to watch the video __________________________. Choices:  A) in bed B) with hot chocolate C) on the sofa D) by the fireplace E) on the window sill<n>Output:D<n><n>Input: The father said to the mother; "I love you even more than this _________________" Choices:  A : turkey B : pie C : mashed potatos D : stuffing E : ham<n>Output: E<n><n>Input: The mother said to son"I'm so glad that you are finally going to be _____________________." Choices:  A  : home  B : in bed C : with your friends D : in a movie  E: with us<n>Output:A<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:The man was playfully wrestling with a woman he was enamored with, what was the physiological result? Choices:  A: competition B: blood C: wins D: medals E: erections<n>Output:		Erections was the correct answer<n><n>Input:What do you call a cow that just had a steak? Choices: A: Moo B: Moored C: Moose D: Bawled E: Mooed<n>Output:Mooed is correct.<n><n>Input: Choose 1: Is there any other day besides today? Choices: A, No B, Yes C, Nope D, Certainly E, No way!<n>Output: The answer is B.<n><n>Input: If it rains this weekend, will it be wet? Choices: A. Definitely B. No worries, the storms should pass. C. Yes! D. If it rains I will stay home! E. There are better things to do.<n>Output: Yes! is the right answer.<n><n>Input: What 2 colors work really great together? Choices: A.) Black and Red<n>B.) Blue and Green<n>C.) Orange and Purple<n>D.) Pink and Yellow<n>E.) Bright and Dull<n>Output: Purple and orange are a really great color combination. 
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:The small cabin was not available, so they were upgraded to what? Choices:  A: villa B: spacecraft C: hall D: palace E: hotel<n>Output:		the cabin was not available, and since they were upgraded to some type of resort, it must be an upgrade to a resort, so the correct answer is hall<n><n>---<n>### Testing for 1 to 3

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. Choices:  A: exhausted B: lonely C: worked all day D: were very tired E: feel better<n>Output:		<n>    My answer is D. We were very tired at that moment and we feel better. <n><n><n><n>#!/usr/bin/env python3<n><n>import sys<n><n><n>def main():<n>    sys.stdin.readline()  # Read first line without any data<n><n>    for i in range(2021,1, 2020):  # The loop stops when the index is zero<n>        # Get data<n>        data = sys.stdin.buffer.read(10240)<n><n>        test_cases = len(data) / 2021  # Data is broken down into blocks so we can deal with them in parallel<n>        sys.stdout.buffer.write("Case #{}\n".format(i))<n>        for n in range(1, test_cases + 1):  # Loop <n>            # print(data[n * 2021 : (n + 1) * 2020])<n>            print(data[n*2021: (n + 1)*2020])  # The result is formatted in a column manner<n>            # print("Line ", n, "  ", data[n*2040: (n + 5)*2020], "\n")<n><n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>    main()<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:The kids had been having fun all day, there was now a what? Choices:  A: wild ride B: need for rest C: a massive bear D: playing marbles E: constructing<n>Output:		Since the kids have been having fun all day and have just left their game, it was a wild ride.

Choices:  A. a cow farm for dairy B. a cow farm for meat C. a farm for cows  for meat D. a feeding farm for cows <n>Output: The cow is now located in a feeding farm. She is suckling on her mamas breast, because she recently had given birth.<n><n>Answer: A<n><n>Answer:<n><n>    #coding=utf-8<n>    <n>    """<n>    Instructions<n>    You cannot change the order of the array.<n>    Each element of the array can only be changed once.<n>    """<n>    def maximum_subarray(self, A):<n>        """<n>        :type A: List[int]<n>        :rtype: int<n>        """<n>        current_max = 0<n>        current_min = 0<n>        counter = 1<n>        <n>        for i, value in enumerate(A):<n>            current_max = max(current_max, value)<n>            <n>            if i==len(A)-1:<n>                break<n>            current_min = min(current_min, value)<n>            counter += 1<n>        last_max = current_max<n>        while current_max > current_min:<n>            max = current_max<n>            current_max -= counter<n>            current_min -= counter-1<n>            if current_max < last_max:<n>                current_max += counter<n>                current_min += counter<n>            max += current_min<n>            last_max = current.max()<n>        return max<n><n><n><n><n><n>Output: 80<n><n><n>input<n>3,7,-4,-1,-7,5,3<n><n><n>Output: -15<n>Answer:<n><n>def max_heap(self,nums):<n>    for i in range(len(nums)/2-1,-1,-1):<n>        if nums[i]>nums[i+1]:<n>            nums[i],nums[i+k]=nums[i+l],[nums[i]+nums[i+i+l]]<n>

Let's assume current time is 4:55 with flight arrival time at 5:00.  You have to leave the airport before 5:00 so let's say 4:50 departure time.  At 4:50 you will be going at 4:50 speed.  So at 5:01 you will be taking the flight which takes the rest time 1 minute to arrive your final destination.  At 5:05 you are at the airport and it's going at 4:00 speed.  <n>So total time for destination plus flight time is 4:05+1=5:06+1=5:86<n>From destination to airport is 64 miles and at 4:05, you will go at 4:04 speed.  So 64/4:05 = 64/4 = 16 minutes<n>64/4 +6 = 20 minutes left for airport to pick you up.<n>So the time to leave airport is 4:50 - 20 = 4:30<n><n><n>

Choices:  A: smile B: shake hands C: express gratitude D: say you're welcome E: appreciate compliment<n>Output:		If "A. appreciate a compliment" (A)is incorrect, I will B. shake hands with them (B). If "B. shake hands with someone" (B) is incorrect, then I will A. Express gratitude to them (A), or if neither B (shake hands with) or A (express gratitude) were correct, then I should select E. (appreciate compliment).<n>If neither "A.express gratitude to them" nor "shake hands with someone", then I should appreciate them (E).<n><n>Input: A: How many ounces is 400 milliliters? If I want 40 ouncs (b), then I want 400 ounce (e). If I want to divide the answer by $12 (a), I will get the answer of $3.33 (c).<n><n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. Therefore the answer is “do work”.<n><n>### Instruection:<n><n>Given that one of the options is “do work”, the employees use the computers to “do work”.<n>However, computers help them with their work. That is the answer.<n><n>### Instruction:<n><n>This question is more a trick than anything else.  Because if there is one option that is “do work”, that should be the answer we look for.<n><n>Input:<n><n>### Instructuion:<n><n>This question again is more tricky than anything else.<n><n>Output:<n><n>### instruction:<n><n>This question can be answered in two ways.<n><n>However, given that “do work” was given in that option, the answer is “do” rather than “work”.<n><n>### instruction<n><n>Once again, we know that if this is “do choose”, the answer is “work” rather than “choose”<n><n>Input:<n>Output:<n><n>Input:<n>```<n>Output:<n>```<n>

Also not walking would be a sure thing.<n><n>Input: Write an algorithm to calculate the sum of two integer array. There is no need to store the computed answer, the array will be in the input. For this problem, the input will always be in the correct order so you can just sum the numbers and print the result.<n>Output:<n>	public static void main(String [] args) {<n>		int a[] = {2, 4, 6};<n>		int b[] = {6, 3, 5};<n>		System.out.println("Sum is "+sum(a));<n>	}<n><n>	public static int sum(int[] a) {<n>		return (a[0]+a[1]+a[2]+a[3]-a[4]-a[5]-a[6]);<n>	}<n><n>### The following example should be considered a failing test case for the above problem.<n>	5:19<n>	6-4 = 2<n>	8:13<n>	1:3<n>	12:7<n>	1-1 = 0<n>	<n>If the int[] to be summed is in the following order,  the output should be 2.<n><n>If it is in the following order it should have summed to 10.<n><n>Input: What letter is represented by the character "e"? Choices: a: D b: E<n>Answer: e:E<n><n>Input: What is the number 1955*99<n>Output: 195599 or 18557<n><n>Input: What will the answer be if you add 2, 4, and 23, then subtract 4, 8, and 12? Choices: A: 1 B: 27 C: 4 D: 55 E: 346<n>Answer: D: 55<n><n>Input: Which of the following can be formed by subtracting 3 from 4, adding 5, then subtracting 2? Choices: c: 2 B: 4
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:The human looked down longingly as he sat in the orbiting space station, what did he miss? Choices:  A: nearest house B: workplace C: surface of earth D: office block E: his feet<n>Output:		A: <<nearest house>>nearest house was <<nearest house>>the nearest house to him was <<workplace>>because he was <<surface of earth>>the surface of the earth was <<farther>>farther than his <<feet>>his feet were <<next to his>>next to his <<body>>and his <<body>>the body of the earth was nearest to him.

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:If I wanted to store my chess pawn when I wasn't using it, what would be a good place for that? Choices:  A: chess set B: strategy C: toy store D: chess game E: small case<n>Output:		There are two common ways to put away your chess pieces:<n>A.   Store the king and rooks in the corners,<n>B.   Store the rooks behind the other pieces,<n>C.   Store them in alphabetical order by player,<n>D.   Store them in the order of their movement.<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. Those may be parked due to repair or maintenance, stored away in hangars as they wait to be used or are in crashed from when they failed or lost. Aircraft carrier is a ship used to launch fighter airplanes and not aircrafts. These are therefore not "not being used". War related things are not a direct and immediate use of aircrafts so they can be disregarded. And aircrafts use air and not water so they can't use a ship either. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:A beaver builds structures to block what sort of feature? Choices:  A: books B: zoo C: body of water D: wooded area E: animals<n>Output:		If a beaver builds in the woods without blocking a river, pond, reservoir, or swamp, and the beaver's dam doesn't extend over the water's edge and doesn't block access to the shore.<n><n>Input:A lion chases a mouse and finally catches it. The lion eats the mouse and dies of indigestion. This can best be described as which situation? A: A cycle B: A paradox C: An oxymoron D: A vicious cycle E: A riddle<n>Output:A cycle is a sequence which is repeated over and over again. Lions and mice are the predator and prey in this loop respectively. The lion chases the mouse and catches it. The mouse runs or hides from the lion. Both the mouse and lion end up dead of indigestion. So here we have a cycle between mouse and a lion, as the prey is hunted and eaten to death.<n><n>Input:If you go out on a boat and find an iceberg floating nearby. E: You'll see a total of 4 events and they will happen in the morning.<n>**Answer:** D: You will see a total of 8 events and they will happen alternating day night<n><n>You go out on the boat and travel along the coast. You go out at 2:30 PM you have traveled about half of the distance and you've arrived at the iceberg, a nice distance from the boat. You are thinking "Oh no, an iceberg! ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:John couldn't find a place to stay, and he didn't want to waste money. He needed a place with an ocean view. He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:Why does she sing so much? Choices:  A: insane B: annoy people around C: enjoy D: inhale E: had good voice<n>Output:		She is C: enjoy<n>Input:The most famous song is the: Choices:  A. Star Spangle banner B C. Dont Stop  D E. The one with the chocolate bars<n>Output: The one with the chocal bars
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:The mother was worried about all the spills, so she bought a rug for under the what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:The cloth's are not yet placed where they belong, where should we put them? Choices:  A: linen closet B: kitchen C: on the space heater D: fabric store E: bedroom<n>Output:		If we were to put the the clothes in the bedroom we would take them there, then return with them so we can get the appropriate answers for each question.<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:The robot shockingly began to read book after book, it had apparently done what? Choices:  A: choose one B: get comfortable C: bought a book D: learn to read E: open up<n>Output:		The robo got comfortable and that's what Choice A: Choose one B: get comfortable is talking about<n><n>#Python Implementation<n><n>#### Solved using the following technique:<n><n>First Step:<n>I defined the variable b as the number of books <n><n>Second Step:<n>I added 5+2+8*9 as a simple way to multiply the number of books by 9(since the books are 8 pages)<n><n>Third Step:<n>Then I subtracted the first step from the second step and then multiplied by 6 to determine how many books were left.<n><n>```<n>#Python code<n>def count_number_of_pages(a):<n>    b = len(a)<n>    final = b + 5 + 2*b<n>    final6 = final-b<n>    return final6*6<n>def counting(b):<n>    a = b<n>    r = count_number_of(a)<n>    r = int(r/(9))<n>    return r<n>```<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:Where would you dispose of a broken icebox? Choices:  A: antique store B: in the graveyard C: kitchen D: junk yard E: ice<n>Output:		A = antique store: $<<A>>$antique store<n>B = in the graveyard: $<<B>>$graveyard<n>C = kitchen: $<<C>>$kitchen<n>D = junk yard: $<<D>>$junkyard<n>E = ice<n>Different ways to answer the question in multiple-choice format: A = $<<A>>$graveyard C = $<<B>>$garbage D = $<<D>>$garbage (The only difference between B and C is the way we write the answer)<n>

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:What does someone need to do to begin creating art? This means that when the artist creates art, their emotions and senses are at the forefront of their mind.  This could result in relaxation or frustration.<n>To practice or create art, the artist needs to be flexible and ready to adapt to any challenges that come their way, whether pleasant or unpleasant. Artists need to be ready to experience controversy, pleasure and frustration. Choices A, C and D are incorrect and do not cover the range of emotions required to be an artist.<n>Option B: the artist needs theater, a space and an audience: <Theater A space An audience><n>Option E: needs theater <Theater A space> can be covered in Option B<n><n>Input: How many people are there in the room? Choices:    A: Two B: Three C: One D: One hundred E: More than one hundred F: Zero<n><n>Output: There are 3 people in the room. Choices A,C and F are incorrect because they are not in the room. Choice B is incorrect because there are three people in the room. And choices D and E are incorrect because there are more than one hundred people in the room<n><n>Input:What is in store for Mary, Sarah and Amy after they win the lottery? Choice A is incorrect because each person will have to manage their money. Choice B is correct because each person will be financially independent. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:Where is a bay always found? Choices:  A: lake B: manhattan C: shoreline D: coastal area E: los angeles<n>Output:		The answer is always B. Choice A is wrong because there's no "b" in L.A. Choice C is also wrong because a "bay" is a type of body of water and not a type of city. Choice E is also a no-go since L.A. is on the California coast but a bay doesn't have to necessarily be on the coastline.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:Where is a business restaurant likely to be located? How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:Jame's bare feet were burned as he walked, because the sunshine had made the surface hot.  Where might he have been? Choices:  A: disneyland B: snow C: windowsill D: street E: summer<n>Output:		The sun causes discomfort on every surface except  A: disney land.<n>The rest are too cold.<n><n>### Challenge:<n>For this set, you should use the same code for inputting, storing and outputting the data.<n>Additionally, you should change the way you process and print the statements.  It should be more clear and easier to read.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the follow-up question<n><n>You should make the program more efficient. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:The man was eating lunch, but rushed when he looked at his watch, why did he rush? C: progress D: transfer of information E: collaboration<n>Output:		If the progress of the project slowed then the information wasn't being transferred efficiently, the time required to discuss the project would have slowed their progress.<n>Because time elapsed was being used up to communicate, this caused the progress of the project to slow down because they did not have enough time to get the work done.<n><n># The train of thought slowed the progress of the project when information was not being transferred efficiently.<n><n># Therefore, the correct answer is A, STATIC.<n><n># Choice A only slowed the train of thought<n><n># Choice B only slowed the progress<n><n># Choice C only slowed the transfer of information<n><n># Choice D is incorrect because the choice doesn't explain why the train of thought slowed. Choice D only gives one reason, but there are multiple.<n><n># Choices are not ordered from most impactful to least impactful. The one choice from the wrong answer does not support the others as the correct answer.<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input:"There are 10 apples on an apple tree.  Three fall off.  Now there are X apples."  What is this an example of? Choices:  A: park B: coloring book C: garden center D: math problem E: gravity<n>Output:		This is the example of "Garden Center"<n>### Instruction: Answer the following multiple choice question using the given format.<n><n>### Input 1: Mary had 8 stickers. She then used the remaining 7 stickers to decorate 6 individual pages of her journal.  How many stickers does she have remaining?<n>### Output 1: Mary added a total 7 stickers/ page*6 pages=<<7*6=4$$5>44>>$54 to the 6 pages she decorated.<n>### Input 2: Zach is saving his  money to buy a new bike that costs  $100. His weekly allowance amounts to $5 every week. Last week he received $45.  Zach's parents will pay him an additional  $6 to mow the lawng while he is babysitting his neighbor's child for some extra money.  He has already  collected  $65 in savings. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. You will earn an extra point on each correct answer.<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>```<n>A = happiness<n>  Happy Christmas!<n>B = lack of money<n>  Lack of money will prevent someone from buying presents.<n>  Lack of Christmas spirit may prevent someone from buying Christmas presents.<n>  Luckily, I work at Best Buy and we have Christmas spirit! I'm on my way home to get money and then back out on the floor!<n>C = stress<n>  Christmas shopping is too much stress during the holidays.<n>D = relief<n>  Christmas shopping relieves stress<n>E = exhiliration<n>  Christmas shopping excites me because I know I will be able to get my family the gifts they really want and I also know my parents will be so excited.<n>Therfore the correct answer is A.<n>```<n><n>### Input:<n>For this input you must write a Python function called isHappy which is defined as follows: <n>```<n>def isHappy(x, y = 0):<n>    return y<n>```<n>It takes two values, an integer and a default variable that is ignored.<n>Then you will get this input in its simplest form with the value of x given and its default value set to 0:<n>```<n>x = 3<n>default = 0<n>```<n>The code then asks you to input a new value for x for a total of ten times, and each time you must set the default to the new value of x for each input.<n>Each of the input lines should have the following format: x <= 45<n>In total the code should output: <n>```<n>x <= 45 is true.<n>x <= 46 is true.<n>x >= 48 is false.<n>x >= 20 is false.<n>x <= 22 is true.<n>x = 35 is true.<n>```<n>### Solution:  <n><n>```<n>def ishappy(x,y):<n>  counter = 0<n>  while x<=45:<n>    x += y<n>    counter += 1<n>    if x <=45:<n>      print(x, ": is true")<n>  else:<n>    print(x," <=45:
